  • Green squares with numbers indicate locations of clusters of activity counters. Click on squares to reveal individual activity counters.
  • Blue dots indicate locations of individual activity counters. Click on dots to access links to individual counter reports or DMF reports.

This report is intended to give a general sense of visitor activity at the Te Araroa trail section level on Public Conservation Land (PCL). Use the embedded links in the tables below to access more detailed information at the individual counter level.

This report uses uncalibrated counter data; i.e., counts represent the number of times the counter sensor has been triggered by a person or bicycle. Uncalibrated counter data must NOT be used to indicate the number of visits or the number of unique visitors to a place. Converting counter data into visits and visitors requires calibration of the data, and should be undertaken with guidance from a DOC Technical Advisor.

Te Araroa Notes

  • To reduce redundancy and complexity, this consolidated report does not include all activity counters installed on PCL trail sections of TA. Counters reported herein have been selected on the basis of TA representation.
  • Some PCL trail sections are dual-use (pedestrian and bicycle), with counts on these sections recording the combined use of walkers and cyclists.
  • Changes in use of trail sections may be attributable to multiple influences; e.g., improved access; social media profile; organised events; etc. Therefore, attribution of change to any single influence, or combination thereof, should not be made without guidance from a DOC Technical Advisor.
  • Some PCL trail sections constitute in part or in whole - highly popular short walks and day hikes. On such sections, the proportion of counts attributable to TA walkers versus other users will be indiscernible in the data.
  • Due to the remote location and technical difficulty of the Waiau Pass trail section, total annual counts on this section are the lowest across all counters referenced in this report. As such, the counts on this section (see Waiau Pass Route counter) are assessed as most likely to reflect the influence of TA walkers.
